JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS AND OTHER - INDIA (20): (BIHAR)
*****************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 19 Sep 2011
Source: Zeenews [edited]
http://zeenews.india.com/news/bihar/japanese-encephalitis-claims-31-lives-in-bihar_732500.html


On Monday [19 Sep 2011], 3 girls suffering from Japanese encephalitis
[virus infections; JE] died in a government hospital here, taking the
statewide toll to 31 in Bihar, officials said. The girls died in
Anugrah Narayan Medical College and Hospital. With this, the total
number of people died due to the fever rose to 31, ANMCH
Superintendent Sitaram Singh said. 2 of the girls were from Gaya
district, while the other was from Nawada district, he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of deaths due to JE virus infections in Bihar state have
increased from 25 on 14 Sep 2011 to 31 just 4 days later.
Interestingly, official government National Vector Borne Disease
Control statistics for JE virus plus the undiagnosed fatal cases of
acute encephalitis syndrome in Bihar state as of 13 Sep 2011 are given
as 54, but do not indicate how many of these are due to JE virus
infections [see ProMED-mail archive number 20110914.2803].

Gaya is the 2nd largest city in Bihar state and the capital of the
district. A HealthMap Interactive map showing the location of Gaya can
be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1emt. - Mod.TY]
